Google Classroom Training for Parents, Grandparents, family members who will be working with students

You might be asking: What is Google Classroom?! This training will begin with a brief overview of Google Classroom and ways you can help your child use it to access classroom materials. Most of the training will be about supporting your child and helping them access emails, classroom materials, complete assignments and make the best of online learning. By the end of the session, you will understand how to help your child with remote learning and feel more comfortable using technology.

07/29/2020
Parents/Students,
Mesa Vista Consolidated Schools will be distributing Chromebooks and other instructional materials to students and parents on Thursday, August 6, 2020 and Friday, August 7, 2020 from 1:00 pm to 4:00 pm both days.
El Rito and Ojo Caliente Elementary students will pick up these materials from their classrooms. High school and middle school will pick up their Chromebooks from the high school library and other materials from classrooms as needed.
Please remember that masks are mandatory and social distancing will strictly be enforced. Feel free to contact me at eric.vigil@mesavista.org if you have any questions or concerns.
Thank you,
Eric Vigil
Mesa Vista Consolidated Schools
Student Engagement Advisor

post_text: The last phases of Pandemic-EBT (P-EBT) will be issued this week. We appreciate your patience with our mail delivery system. P-EBT cards should be delivered by Mid-July. In addition to the card that will be mailed to the families, a set of instructions on how to activate the card will be included. The parent will need the date of birth of the eldest student, the first and last name of the student, and card number. If you would like to distribute this information to the families in your school community, please see this press release for complete information:

Please help us spread the word to New Mexico Educators! Join us for a virtual Town Hall on Tuesday, June 30th from 3:00pm - 4:30pm. Lt. Governor Howie Morales, Secretary Ryan Stewart and our Deputy Secretaries will answer your questions about school reentry. All educators are invited to join but registration is required be on the Zoom webinar. This event will also be live-streamed to Facebook, no registration required. Questions may be submitted in advance when you register, or submitted via the Q&A feature during the Zoom call. Unfortunately, we are not able to take questions directly from Facebook. https://bit.ly/EducatorTownHall

post_text:
Mesa Vista Consolidated School District Thanks all those instrumental in helping during the COVID-19 pandemic.

The Mesa Vista Consolidated School would like to thank the many people responding to the COVID pandemic. From doctors and nurses caring for people on the front lines, to delivery and truck drivers, first responders, and grocery store workers ensuring the availability of essential goods and services.

We would especially like to thank District educators, food and nutrition services workers, information technology staff, and custodial staff for going above and beyond to make sure the needs of our students, families, and staff were met.

Thank you!

Thank you to the seniors that wanted to participate in our Facebook senior showcase. We appreciate you all and are so thanksful that Mesa Vista Consolidated Schools was part of your journey.
We want to celebrate all your accomplishments and more! We will never forget the class of 2020 and all the sacrifices you had to make. Congratulations CLASS OF 2020!!!

post_text:
“Getting to Know” our Mesa Vista Class of 2020.

RYAN GARCIA

We asked these 5 questions.

1. Where do you plan on going to college and what do you plan on majoring in?
- I will be attending Texas Tech University and will be majoring in Environmental Engineering.

2.If you could create one mandatory course for future seniors, what would it be?
- One mandatory course for future seniors would be life lessons.

3. If you could change one school rule, what would it be?
- One school rule that I could change would be to have more breaks.

4. Describe your senior year in three words.
- Memorable, unique, and accomplishment.

5.”I will always remember…”
- I will always remember my time in high school. The experiences, friends, teachers, and lessons are something that will always be a reminder of where I started.

We need to take a moment and fill out the #2020Census and if you need help, Please message or contact Steph Census.

You can respond online, by phone and mail.
The federal funding that will be given to the communities is based on population.
The federal funding is used for many different programs in our communities from Fire Departments, Schools, Headstart Programs, Senior Citizen Programs, Veteran Programs, Hospitals, Clinics to help fix roads and build new ones.

It takes only a few minutes to complete, so take a moment, grab some coffee, tea, soda, or anything refreshing and fill out the survey.

post_text: MVHS is pleased to announce the appointment of Leonard Torrez Jr. as the Head Coach of the girls basketball team for the 20/21 school year. Mr. Torrez is an Alumnus of Mesa Vista schools and is excited to return home to Mesa Vista to continue the advancement of athletics at MVHS after a 9 year tenure at Española schools. If you have a/or are an incoming 7th grade through 12th grader and are interested in playing this upcoming season, you can contact coach at CoachL.Torrez@gmail.com with your age and grade and a short bio about yourself. He will contact you back with more information about offseason workouts and further communication methods that are planned for the team.

Staff/Students/Parents,

MVHS will be allowing students grades 7-11 access to their lockers on Monday, April 6, 2020 from 9:00 am to 11:00 am.

Students will check in at the gate with Security and allowed on campus 5 at a time. Anyone entering the building will be expected to practice social distancing, 6 to 10 feet apart from each other. This time should be used to get necessities from your lockers as quickly as possible and not to socialize.

Mrs. Lujan’s students will need to see her for packet pick up, she will be in her classroom at this time. Also, Mr. Jaramillo will be in the High School area to answer any questions.

Please contact Eric Vigil, Student Engagement Advisor, at eric.vigil@mesavista.org if you have any questions or concerns.

Please email any ideas/thoughts/suggestions concerning the budget for the 2020-2021 school year to Superintendent Martinez at albert.martinez@mesavista.org by April 10th.
Thank you for all your guidance and support.

March 19 at 3:50 PM ·

Our Wi-Fi Hot Spot is up and running! Huge thanks to Kit Carson for providing this FREE service to our community. During regular business hours we'll have the gate to our parking area open (remember the library is closed). Come into the lot in your vehicles and help yourself to the Wi-Fi (the speed is quicker than ours indoors, great news). Or on warm days, feel free to sit outside on our porches or benches - but PLEASE observe SAFE social distancing with others. We suggest staying 6 feet from those not in your group when using the internet outside. Thank you again to Kit Carson!

Log into: Kit Carson Guest Wi-Fi
Password (follow upper/lower cases): Kitc@rson2020

Mr.Apodaca and Staff would like to congratulate the following MesaVista High School Students for receiving the following Scholarships:

Senator Pete Domenici Scholarships, named after the late U.S. Senator (R-N.M.), are $10,000 awards given to one recipient from each of the seven counties served by the scholarship program. Recipients of the Domenici Scholarships are:

Michael Ryan Garcia, Mesa Vista High School (Rio Arriba County)

Mesa Vista High School graduates are the beneficiaries of the $1,000 Tim Martin Memorial Scholarship. This year’s awards went to Gabriella Archuleta, Michael Ryan Garcia (also a Domenici Scholar), and Daniel Gollas.
